04645nam a22005655i 9780773597426DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735974267 a10.1515/97807735974262doi  a(DE-B1597)657283  a(OCoLC)909957060  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1053.2b.C53 2015 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a324.2714060921 aCiaccia, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCall Me Giambattista :bA Personal and Political Journey /cJohn Ciaccia. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b28 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFootprints Series ;v2100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tArrival in a New Land -- tThe Law Beckons -- tWorking for Mr Sam -- tThe View from Place Ville Marie -- tOn to Indian Affairs -- tEntering the Political Arena -- tBill 22 Stirs Up a Hornet’s Nest -- tThe James Bay Challenge -- tDawn of a New Era -- tThe Elected Representative -- tThe Referendum Divides Quebec -- tAnother Election -- tA Constitutional Quandary -- tThe Hearings on the Damage to the James Bay Project -- tBack in Power -- tAnother Language Crisis -- tMinister of International Affairs -- tOka – a Failure of Understanding* -- tMeech Lake and Charlottetown: Attempts at Constitutional Change -- tDoubts, Uncertainty, and a Referendum -- tThe Last Hurrah -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat draws a person to the political life? In Call Me Giambattista, John Ciaccia recounts his immigration to Canada from Italy as a small child in 1937 to his retirement from the National Assembly of Quebec in 1998. After studying at McGill University's Faculty of Law, practising in a Montreal law firm, and shifting gears to work as a federal civil servant, a phone call in 1973 from Premier Robert Bourassa launched Ciaccia's twenty-five-year career in Quebec politics. As a member federalist politician from an Italian background, Ciaccia faced many challenges. When first elected, he negotiated the James Bay Agreement with the Cree and the Inuit, and later, as Quebec's minister of Native Affairs, he was a key negotiator in the Oka crisis of 1990. Over the course of his career he held four cabinet posts, including International Affairs, and he ended his political career as the longest-serving member of the National Assembly. Ciaccia details all of these events and more, and explains his relationships with leading figures such as Robert Bourassa, Claude Ryan, Pierre Trudeau, René Lévesque, and Jacques Parizeau. Revealing his approach to politics, Ciaccia describes the lessons he learned from his career, and underscores the importance of acting according to one's convictions. An intriguing memoir of an Italian immigrant who came to hold key roles in the Quebec government, Call Me Giambattista tells the story of a political leader and the choices he made during a seminal period in Quebec history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLawyerszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aLawyerszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aPoliticianszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aPoliticianszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359742640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773597426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773597426/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2